instructions\/4\/text: Place three quarters of the white chocolate in a heat-proof glass bowl and put it in the microwave on high for 30 seconds.
instructions\/5\/text: (Time it with your watch for accuracy.)
instructions\/6\/text: Stir the chocolate with a rubber spatula, return it to the microwave for another 30 seconds, then stir again.
instructions\/7\/text: Continue to heat and stir in 30-second intervals until the chocolate is just melted.
instructions\/8\/text: Immediately stir in the remaining chocolate and allow it to sit at room temperature, stirring often, until it's completely smooth.
instructions\/9\/text: (If you need to heat it a little more, place it in the microwave for another 15 seconds.)
instructions\/10\/text: Pour the melted chocolate onto the parchment paper and spread it lightly to fill the drawn rectangle.
instructions\/11\/text: Sprinkle the top evenly with the cooled pistachios, the cranberries, and apricots.
instructions\/12\/text: Press the nuts and fruit lightly so they will set in the chocolate.
instructions\/13\/text: Set aside for at least 2 hours until firm or refrigerate for 20 minutes.
instructions\/14\/text: Cut or break the bark in 16 pieces and serve at room temperature.

instructions\/4\/text: It will still be a little lumpy, although it will gather into a ball around the hook.
instructions\/5\/text: Pull it off the dough hook and knead it by hand for a few strokes on an unfloured surface until it is very smooth and springy.
instructions\/6\/text: (Alternatively, scrape the dough onto a lightly floured surface and knead with smooth, steady strokes until silky smooth and springy, 10 to 12 minutes.
instructions\/7\/text: Avoid kneading extra flour into the dough.)
instructions\/8\/text: Transfer the dough to a lightly oiled, clear, 2-quart straight-sided container with a lid.
instructions\/9\/text: With masking tape, mark the spot on the container where the dough will be once it has increased 1 1/2 times in volume.
instructions\/10\/text: Cover and leave it to rise at room temperature (70 to 75 degrees) for 45 minutes.
instructions\/11\/text: It will increase by about 25 percent.
instructions\/12\/text: Lightly dust a work surface with flour and, using a bench scraper or spatula, empty the risen dough out of the container.
instructions\/13\/text: Pat it gently into a rectangle, about 6 x 8 inches, and fold it into thirds like a business letter.
instructions\/14\/text: With the short side facing you, lift the top edge and fold it into the center of the rectangle; lift the near edge and fold it into the center so that it overlaps the top edge by about 1-inch.
instructions\/15\/text: Quickly slide both hands under the dough and flip it over so the folds are underneath.
instructions\/16\/text: Slip it back into the container, pushing it down to fit.
instructions\/17\/text: Cover the dough and let it rise in a warm and draft-free spot until it expands, reaching halfway to the masking tape mark.
instructions\/18\/text: 45 minutes to 1 hour.
instructions\/19\/text: About 1 hour before baking, place a baking stone on the middle rack of the oven and a cast-iron skillet on the lower rack.
instructions\/20\/text: Preheat the oven to 450 degrees.
instructions\/21\/text: (If you are baking the breads on a baking sheet, its only necessary to preheat the oven about 20 minutes before baking.)
instructions\/22\/text: Lightly dust your work surface with flour.
instructions\/23\/text: Uncover the dough and turn it out onto the work surface.
instructions\/24\/text: With a bench scraper or chefs knife, cut the dough into 3 equal pieces.
instructions\/25\/text: Gently pat each piece into a rough rectangle and fold it in half.
instructions\/26\/text: Sprinkle the pieces of dough with flour and lightly drape them with plastic wrap.
instructions\/27\/text: Let them relax on the counter for 10 minutes.
instructions\/28\/text: Cover a bakers peel or rimless baking sheet with parchment paper and lightly dust with flour.
instructions\/30\/text: On a lightly floured work surface, pat the dough into a rough rectangle measuring about 3 x 5 inches.
instructions\/31\/text: With the longer side facing you, fold the top of the dough down about one-third of the way toward the center.
instructions\/32\/text: With the heel of your hand, press along the seam using firm but gentle pressure.
instructions\/33\/text: Fold the bottom of the dough about one-third of the way toward the center and seal the seam firmly.
instructions\/34\/text: Fold this skinny rectangle in half, bringing the top edge down to meet the bottom edge.
instructions\/35\/text: Working from right to left, cup your hand over the log of dough arid press the heel of your hand down firmly to seal the seam.
instructions\/36\/text: Dust the work surface with additional flour to prevent the dough from sticking.
instructions\/37\/text: To stretch the log, place your hands together, palms down, over the middle of the log.
instructions\/38\/text: Using light, even pressure, roll the log back and forth as you spread your hands apart.
instructions\/39\/text: Repeat 3 or 4 times until the log is the desired length, about 14 inches long.
instructions\/41\/text: Place the baguettes on the parchment, seam sides down, about 2 inches apart.
instructions\/42\/text: Lift the parchment between the loaves, making pleats and drawing the loaves together.
instructions\/43\/text: Tightly roll two kitchen towels and slip them under the parchment paper on the sides of the two outer loaves to support and cradle the baguettes.
instructions\/44\/text: Lightly dust the tops of the baguettes with flour and gently drape them with plastic wrap.
instructions\/45\/text: Let the loaves stand at room temperature for 30 to 40 minutes.
instructions\/46\/text: They will increase about 1 1/2 times in size.
instructions\/47\/text: Uncover the loaves, take away the towels, and stretch the parchment paper out so it is flat and the loaves are separated.
instructions\/48\/text: Score each baguette with a single-edge razor blade or a serrated knife.
instructions\/49\/text: Starting from the tip, angle the blade 45 degrees to make 3 slashes about 3 inches long and 1/2-inch deep.
instructions\/50\/text: Slide the loaves, still on the parchment, onto the hot baking stone or rimless baking sheet.
instructions\/51\/text: Place 1/2 cup of ice in the hot cast-iron skillet and slide back onto the lower rack to produce steam.
instructions\/52\/text: Bake the baguettes until caramel colored, 15 to 20 minutes.
instructions\/53\/text: Slide the peel or baking sheet under the parchment paper to remove the loaves from the oven.
instructions\/54\/text: Slide the loaves, still on the parchment, onto a wire rack to cool.
instructions\/55\/text: Eat them warm or at room temperature.
instructions\/56\/text: Freeze leftover baguettes in resealable plastic bags for up to 1 month.

title: Fresh Corn Tortillas
instructions\/1\/text: Put the masa in the bowl of a standing mixer fitted with the hook attachment.
instructions\/2\/text: Beat at low speed while gradually adding 1 cup of the water.
instructions\/3\/text: Add as much of the remaining water 1 tablespoon at a time as needed to make a soft and smooth dough.
instructions\/4\/text: The dough is the right consistency when a small piece of it can be rolled into a ball between your palms without the dough cracking.
instructions\/5\/text: Beat for 1 minute more, then use the dough immediately.
instructions\/6\/text: Roll 3 level tablespoons (1 1/2 ounces) of the dough between your palms to make a 2-inch ball.
instructions\/7\/text: Line the bottom plate of tortilla press with a circle of plastic (cut from a plastic grocery store bag).
instructions\/8\/text: Center the dough over the plastic, top with a second circle of plastic, and press the dough out ot a smooth circle, wiggling the handle of the press gently to flatten the dough evenly.
instructions\/9\/text: Lift the top of the press, rotate the dough circle so the front of the circle is now at the back, and press again.
instructions\/10\/text: (Most tortilla presses will make tortillas that are slightly thicker on one side than the other.
instructions\/11\/text: Rotating the tortilla after the first press will make an evenly thick tortilla that will cook evenly.)
instructions\/12\/text: As soon as the tortilla is pressed, place it on the griddle.
instructions\/13\/text: Cook until the underside start to turn light golden brown in spots, about 2 minutes.
instructions\/14\/text: Turn and cook unitl the tortilla puffs up.
instructions\/15\/text: Repeat with the remaining masa, transferring the hot tortillas to a napkin-lined basket if serving them immediately or stacking them on a plate if using them for another recipe.
instructions\/16\/text: Once you get the hang of it, youll be able to press more tortilla while those on the griddle continue cooking.

instructions\/4\/text: Keep the water in the pot at roughly the same level with hourly additions of 2 cups water until the peanuts are soft (South Carolina-style peanuts are very soft, but some cooks prefer them al dente).
instructions\/5\/text: When the peanuts have boiled for 3 hours, sample them to check for texture and saltiness.
instructions\/6\/text: Allow a peanut to cool, then crack open the shell to get at the kernels inside.
instructions\/7\/text: If you find them too salty, remove some brine with a ladle or small pot and replace it with an equal amount of fresh water.
instructions\/8\/text: If the peanuts are not salty enough, add salt in 1/4 cup increments, turn off the heat, and let them soak for an hour to absorb the salt.
instructions\/9\/text: If the peanuts are too crunchy for your taste, boil on.
instructions\/10\/text: It can take as long as 12 hours if you prefer them mushroom-soft.
instructions\/11\/text: Sample them every hour.
instructions\/12\/text: When the peanuts are cooked to your satisfaction, turn off the heat and cool for 1 hour.
instructions\/13\/text: When cool enough to handle, drain and eat immediately or store (in the shell) in a sealed container in the refrigerator or freezer.

instructions\/17\/text: Many have shared that this recipe is great served warm or cold with just sprinkling powdered sugar on top!

instructions\/4\/text: Dough should be very crumbly, and not really hold together.
instructions\/5\/text: Add olive oil and the rest of the water/yeast mixture, and continue to combine by hand until dough is soft and smooth.

instructions\/7\/text: Place dough on a flat surface and vigorously knead for about 10 minutes.

instructions\/9\/text: Put dough in a greased bowl (or a lightly oiled bowl), and make sure grease/oil covers the outside of the dough.
instructions\/10\/text: Let rise for 45-60 minutes in a warm (80-90 degree) place.
instructions\/11\/text: Once dough has risen (increased to about double in size), punch it down (about three firm punches to the dough's surface), knead for another 2-3 minutes, and allow to rise again, per the instructions above).
instructions\/12\/text: Repeat this step for a total of three rises.
instructions\/13\/text: After the dough has risen for the third time, separate into two pieces (or more, if smaller pizzas are desired).
instructions\/14\/text: Roll pizzas out into 13-14 inch circles and top as desired.
instructions\/15\/text: Bake in a 475 degree oven for 20-25 minutes, or until crust is crispy and golden brown.
instructions\/16\/text: A baking stone is strongly recommended.
instructions\/17\/text: If using a baking stone, lightly sprinkle with corn meal to prevent sticking.
instructions\/18\/text: To parbake (half bake the dough, and save for later), follow the above baking directions, but only bake for 8-10 minutes.
instructions\/19\/text: Allow to cool, wrap in plastic wrap, and refrigerate for up to 24 hours, or freeze so they'll last longer.
instructions\/20\/text: Alternative baking method - if your oven has the capability to do so, preheat oven and baking stone to 600 degrees.
instructions\/21\/text: Adjust cooking time to 5-10 minutes, or until crust is crispy and golden brown.
instructions\/22\/text: This method can also utilize bread flour, as it cooks at a high enough temperature to allow the bread flour to rise properly during cooking, yet not allow the glutens to break down during cooking and cause the dough to collapse, thus making for a soggy pizza.
instructions\/23\/text: This is my preferred method, as it allows for a reduced cooking time and more of a "brick oven pizza" flavor and crispiness.
instructions\/24\/text: It's also the preferable method to cook pizzas with more liquid ingredients, such as tomato sauce, fresh tomatoes, etc.

title: New York Deli-Style Bagels
instructions\/1\/text: Let mixture sit 5 minutes until yeast is foamy, then stir with a fork until yeast dissolves.
instructions\/2\/text: In a large bowl or bowl of a stand mixer, stir together flour and salt.
instructions\/3\/text: Make a well in the center; add yeast mixture.
instructions\/4\/text: Pour half of the remaining warm water into the bowl; stir to combine.
instructions\/5\/text: Mix, adding remaining water as needed until a smooth dough forms.
instructions\/6\/text: Knead dough by hand on a lightly floured countertop, adding more flour as needed until a stiff, firm but smooth and elastic dough forms, about 10 minutes; or, increase speed of stand mixer to medium and knead dough with a dough hook, adding more flour as needed until a stiff, firm but smooth and elastic dough forms, about 5-6 minutes.
instructions\/7\/text: Shape dough into ball and place in a lightly greased bowl.
instructions\/8\/text: Cover with plastic wrap or a tea towel and let rise in a warm place until doubled, about 1 hour.
instructions\/9\/text: (Pro tip: If your kitchen is chilly in the winter like mine is, put the bowl in the microwave, on top of a towel-lined heating pad on the lowest setting or in an unheated oven with the oven light turned on.)
instructions\/10\/text: Once dough is doubled in size, punch down and let rest 10 minutes.
instructions\/11\/text: Divide dough into 8 equal pieces.
instructions\/12\/text: Roll each piece of dough into a smooth ball.
instructions\/13\/text: Use your finger to poke a hole in the center of each ball, stretching the hole until it is as big as half the diameter of the entire bagel (it might look too big at first, but it will shrink when you boil/bake it).
instructions\/14\/text: Place bagels on a lightly greased or silicone mat-lined baking sheet.
instructions\/15\/text: Cover with a damp towel or lightly greased plastic wrap and let rest 10 minutes.
instructions\/16\/text: Meanwhile, preheat the oven to 425 degrees F. Bring a large pot of water to a boil, then reduce heat to just below a simmer.
instructions\/17\/text: Using a slotted spoon, lower a few bagels at a time into the water.
instructions\/18\/text: Allow bagels to float to the top.
instructions\/19\/text: Leave bagels in the water 1-2 minutes, then flip over and leave in the water another 1-2 minutes (the longer they stay in the water, the chewier they become).
instructions\/20\/text: Remove bagels with slotted spoon and return to prepared baking sheet.
instructions\/21\/text: Repeat with remaining bagels.
instructions\/22\/text: Bake until golden brown, about 15-20 minutes.
instructions\/23\/text: Remove from oven and let cool completely on a cooling rack before slicing.
instructions\/24\/text: Recipe adapted from The Sophisticated Gourmet.

instructions\/7\/text: While almonds are still warm, place in bowl of food processor.
instructions\/8\/text: Remove plunger or food pusher from small central tube in lid.
instructions\/9\/text: This will allow steam and moisture to escape during processing.
instructions\/10\/text: Process for 12 minutes until almonds are broken down and take on a mealy appearance.
instructions\/11\/text: Stop food processor, remove lid and scrape down sides of processing bowl.
instructions\/12\/text: Snap processor lid in place and continue processing almonds until smooth and loosely creamy.
instructions\/13\/text: This may take up to 15 minutes (or longer in some machines).
instructions\/14\/text: Stop food processor as necessary to scrape down sides of processing bowl.
instructions\/15\/text: During processing, almonds will go through several stages, including a point where most of almond butter will come together into a ball.
instructions\/16\/text: Please note: The food processor may become unstable during this stage and walk across countertop.
instructions\/17\/text: Simply hold it in place with your hands.
instructions\/18\/text: The ball stage precedes the smoothing out stage where almonds become a smooth almond butter.
instructions\/19\/text: When almond butter has reached desired consistency (see notes), stop food processor.
instructions\/20\/text: Add remaining ingredients and process for 30 seconds ro 1 minute until well combined.
instructions\/21\/text: Store, covered, in a glass jar in a cool, dry place for up to 1 month or in the refrigerator for up to 3 months.
instructions\/22\/text: Notes: 1.
instructions\/23\/text: Be attentive when roasting almonds.
instructions\/24\/text: They can easily burn in the later stage of roasting.
instructions\/25\/text: Be sure to check them at the 12-minute mark; they may be ready at that time or it could take up to 15 minutes.
instructions\/27\/text: When processing, after the ball stage, almond butter will smooth out.
instructions\/29\/text: Continued processing will cause almond butter to thin out until it becomes the consistency of honey.
instructions\/30\/text: The processing can be stopped at any point after the ball stage, depending on personal texture preferences.

title: Jamaican Ginger Pralines
instructions\/1\/text: Also, have handy 2 tablespoons to use for dipping and dropping the candy.
instructions\/2\/text: Line 3 baking sheets with parchment paper or foil, butter generously; set aside.
instructions\/3\/text: (Don't use wax paper; the candy will stick to it.
instructions\/5\/text: Combine in a heavy 3-quart saucepan the sugar, baking soda, buttermilk, corn syrup, ginger, butter, rum or vanilla extract.
instructions\/6\/text: Place the pan on medium-high heat and bring the syrup to a boil, stirring until the sugar is completely dissolved, for 6 to 8 minutes.
instructions\/7\/text: Then, cover the pan and boil the syrup without stirring for 3 minutes.
instructions\/8\/text: (Stirring will make the mixture grainy.)
instructions\/9\/text: Remove the cover.
instructions\/10\/text: Dip the pastry brush into the water and brush down the sides of the pan.
instructions\/11\/text: Attach the candy thermometer to the inside of the pot.
instructions\/12\/text: Cook the syrup without stirring until it reaches 225 degrees, frequently brushing down the pan with the damp brush.
instructions\/13\/text: Quickly scatter the pecans or walnuts over the syrup and continue cooking until the syrup reaches 236 degrees or the soft ball stage and is deep amber in color.
instructions\/14\/text: Watch carefully, because the candy cooks quickly at this point and can burn.
instructions\/15\/text: Remove the thermometer.
instructions\/16\/text: Add the rum or vanilla extract and butter and swirl the pan until combined.
instructions\/17\/text: Then move quickly to the work area.
instructions\/18\/text: Using the 2 tablespoons and, working quickly, scoop the candy with 1 tablespoon and use the second spoon to push the candy onto the baking sheet, dropping the candies about 2 inches apart.
instructions\/19\/text: Allow the pralines to cool and let stand until firm and crunchy and the consistency of hard fudge, at least an hour or longer.
instructions\/20\/text: The pralines can be stored in airtight containers for a week or so.

instructions\/0\/text: In a mixer fitted with a paddle attachment, or using a hand mixer, mix the flour, salt, and sugar for 1 minute.
title: Perfect Pie Crust (Very Detailed Instructions)
instructions\/1\/text: Add the butter and mix just until you have a crumbly, sandy mixture.
instructions\/2\/text: (You should still be able to see the pieces of butter.)
instructions\/3\/text: In a small bowl, stir the water and vinegar together.
instructions\/4\/text: With the mixer running at medium speed, drizzle in the water-vinegar mixture and mix just until a dough forms.
instructions\/5\/text: (You should still see small bits of butter.)
instructions\/6\/text: Transfer the dough to a work surface and shape into a round, flat disk.
instructions\/7\/text: Wrap in plastic wrap and refrigerate at least 30 minutes before using.
instructions\/8\/text: Or, refrigerate up to 48 hours or freeze up to 1 month before using.
instructions\/9\/text: If frozen, let thaw in the refrigerator overnight before rolling out.)
instructions\/10\/text: When the time comes to roll out the dough, let the dough warm up for a few minutes at room temperature to make it more workable.
instructions\/11\/text: Dust a work surface with just a few tablespoons of flour and keep some extra flour at hand.
instructions\/12\/text: Sprinkle a little flour on top of the dough and start rolling outward from the center with quick, light strokes.
instructions\/13\/text: Don't worry if the edges split a bit; concentrate on forming a good circle from the center.
instructions\/14\/text: Lift up and rotate the dough 1/4 turn every minute or so to help ensure even rolling.
instructions\/15\/text: The dough should feel smooth and soft; some say it should feel like the inside of your forearm.
instructions\/16\/text: If it gets sticky, sprinkle on a bit more flour, but don't do this more than 2 or 3 times; the dough will absorb too much flour.
instructions\/17\/text: Instead, put it back in the refrigerator for 15 minutes to firm up the butter.
instructions\/18\/text: Keep rolling until the circle is at least 2 inches larger than your pan (for example, 12 inches wide for a 10-inch pie pan), or 3 inches larger for deep-dish pies.
instructions\/19\/text: Set your pie pan nearby.
instructions\/20\/text: To transfer the crust to the pan, I find it easiest to roll a finished crust up onto the rolling pin, then gently unroll it in the pan.
instructions\/21\/text: Or, you can fold it gently in quarters, lift it up, position the center point on the center of the pan, and unfold it into the pan.
instructions\/22\/text: Make sure that the dough is allowed to settle completely into the pan.
instructions\/23\/text: Don't stretch and press the dough into the corners; stretched dough will likely shrink back when you bake it.
instructions\/24\/text: Instead, lift the edges of the crust to let it settle down into the corners.
instructions\/25\/text: If the dough tears a bit, don't be concerned; we'll patch it in a minute.
instructions\/26\/text: Using scissors or a sharp knife, trim the dough to within 3/4-inch of the rim.
instructions\/27\/text: Use any extra scraps to patch the crust, pressing with your fingers (wet them if necessary) or set aside.
instructions\/28\/text: To decorate the rim, fold under the excess dough then just press it all around with the back of a fork.
instructions\/29\/text: For a slightly more advanced look, press the thumb and forefinger of one hand together.
instructions\/30\/text: Use them to gently push the thick dough rim outward, while pushing inward with the forefinger of the other hand, so that they intersect in a "V" with the dough in between.
instructions\/32\/text: Repeat all around the rim to make a wavy edge.
instructions\/33\/text: If baking with the filling, chill until ready.

instructions\/18\/text: If your pan becomes rusted, simply scour and re-season.
instructions\/19\/text: A well-seasoned pan will naturally darken with use.
instructions\/20\/text: Do not leave food in pan after cooking.

instructions\/2\/text: Let the mix rise for 12 hours or until it looks double in size and very bubbly.
instructions\/3\/text: Make the cooked pre-dough.
instructions\/4\/text: Mix the cooked pre-dough ingredients (60 g whole grain spelt, 290 ml water and 13 g salt) in a small pot.
instructions\/5\/text: Heat on medium low until it thickens up.
instructions\/6\/text: Make sure you whisk or stir it while it's cooking so there are no clumps.
instructions\/7\/text: Let cool for a couple hours before mixing the main dough, or do up to 2 days ahead and store in the fridge - just bring to room temp before using.
instructions\/8\/text: Time to make the main dough!
ingredients\/8\/text: leavening agents, yeast, baker's, active dry
instructions\/9\/text: Mix together the bubbly pre-dough, cooked pre-dough and the rest of the ingredients except for the seeds and raisins.
instructions\/10\/text: Remove to a floured surface and knead until the dough comes together.
instructions\/11\/text: Fold the raisins into the dough.
instructions\/12\/text: Note: the dough is probably quite soft so sprinkle flour on your hands and the surface if it's sticking too much.
instructions\/13\/text: Knead the dough for about 10 minutes.
instructions\/14\/text: If it's sticking a lot, just continuously stretch a little and fold over itself.
instructions\/15\/text: After about 10 minutes, it will become smooth and elastic.
instructions\/16\/text: Fold in the flax and sunflower seeds and knead another minute.
instructions\/17\/text: Form into a ball and place in a large bowl.
instructions\/18\/text: Cover with plastic wrap and let rise for about 1 hour or until doubled.
instructions\/19\/text: Remove the dough from the bowl and onto a floured surface.
instructions\/20\/text: Form into a oblong or round loaf.
instructions\/21\/text: Place the loaf, with the crease facing up, into oblong pot or round bowl lined with a well-floured cloth.
instructions\/22\/text: If you have a banneton/proofing basket, you can use that!
instructions\/23\/text: Let it rise another 1 hour.
instructions\/24\/text: After rising it should have increased in size considerably.
instructions\/25\/text: While rising, preheat the oven to 480F/350C.
instructions\/26\/text: Place a metal or class oven dish filled with about 1-2 inches (5-10 cm) water on the bottom rack - it will create steam that makes the bread better :)
instructions\/27\/text: Once the oven is preheated and the pan of water is simmering, remove the dough from the cloth or basket and onto a lined baking sheet with the crease facing down.
instructions\/28\/text: Quickly cut 2 slits across the top and immediately place in the oven on the center rack (watch out for the steam when opening the oven!)
instructions\/29\/text: Bake for 8 minutes with the steam at 480F/350C.
instructions\/30\/text: Then remove the pan of boiling water and lower the oven heat to 400F/200C.
instructions\/32\/text: Remove and let cool on a rack for 1-2 hours.

instructions\/1\/text: Put the bread flour in a bowl.

instructions\/3\/text: Pour the milk on the yeast.
instructions\/4\/text: Mix with a rubber spatula and transfer the mixture on to a work surface.
instructions\/5\/text: Knead with the lower part of your palm (near your wrist), rubbing the dough from closest to you and stretch out.
instructions\/6\/text: It will be sticky for a while, but it will clump up eventually.
instructions\/7\/text: (The picture doesn't look good but...)
instructions\/8\/text: When it clumps, pour the canola oil on the dough and rub with both of your hands.
instructions\/9\/text: The dough will absorb the oil after a while.
instructions\/10\/text: When the dough has absorbed the oil, repeat the process of rubbing the dough a few times.
instructions\/11\/text: Use your wrist, pound the dough onto the work space and then fold it into half, pound the dough again and fold it into half.
instructions\/12\/text: Repeat the pounding and folding process a few times.
instructions\/13\/text: When the surface of the dough becomes smooth, roll the dough into a ball while pulling and tucking the surface in.
instructions\/14\/text: (Don't let go of the dough when you are pounding it.
instructions\/15\/text: Pound the dough like you are stretching it.)
instructions\/16\/text: Cover the bowl with the dough using a shower cap.
instructions\/17\/text: Let it sit for the 1st proofing in a warm place until the dough doubles in size.
instructions\/18\/text: I recommend keeping it by a window that gets a lot of sun or in a car.
instructions\/19\/text: When the dough has risen, coat your finger with flour and do the finger check.
instructions\/20\/text: If you poke a hole in the dough but it closes up soon after you take your finger out, let it sit a little bit more.
instructions\/21\/text: Gently punch down the dough and divide it into 3 portions using a bench scraper.
instructions\/22\/text: Tuck the cut ends in and roll into balls.
instructions\/23\/text: Let it sit for 15 minutes, making sure that it doesn't dry out.
instructions\/24\/text: Roll out the dough out and fold into thirds.
instructions\/25\/text: Seal the joint parts well using your finger.
instructions\/26\/text: (You can roll the dough any way you like.)
instructions\/27\/text: Line the balls of dough in the pan as shown, with one in the center and two on the ends.
instructions\/28\/text: If you want to give the bread a rounded top, let the dough rise to 1 to 2 cm higher than the mold.
instructions\/29\/text: If you want the bread to be a square shape on top, let the dough rise to 2 cm lower than the mold.
instructions\/30\/text: Bake in a 360F/180C oven for 30 minutes.
instructions\/31\/text: Cover with an aluminum foil if it starts to burn.

instructions\/33\/text: Top with pizza cheese in the cut and bake.
instructions\/35\/text: Brown Sugar Bread When you roll out the dough after the 1st proofing, sprinkle some brown sugar and roll, then let it sit for the 2nd proofing.

instructions\/1\/text: Set the mixture aside.
instructions\/2\/text: To make the dough: Combine all of the dough ingredients and mix and knead everything together, by hand, mixer or bread machine set on the dough cycle, till you've made a smooth dough.
instructions\/3\/text: If you're kneading in a stand mixer, it should take about 7 minutes at second speed, and the dough should barely clean the sides of the bowl, perhaps sticking a bit at the bottom.

instructions\/5\/text: Place the dough in a lightly greased bowl or other rising container.

instructions\/7\/text: Rising may take longer, especially if you've kneaded by hand.

ingredients\/11\/text: milk, fluid, 1% fat, without added vitamin a and vitamin d

instructions\/17\/text: You'll make two or more layers.

instructions\/19\/text: Cover the pan, and let the bread rise for 1 to 2 hours, until it's quite puffy, though not doubled in bulk.
instructions\/20\/text: You'll start to see white dough through the chocolate coating as they bread rises.
instructions\/21\/text: Towards the end of the rising time, preheat the oven to 350F
instructions\/22\/text: Bake the bread for about 30 to 35 minutes, till you can see it starting to brown underneath the chocolate.
instructions\/23\/text: An instant-read thermometer inserted into the center of the loaf will register about 190F
instructions\/24\/text: Remove the bread from the oven, and sprinkle it with the chocolate chips.

instructions\/26\/text: Take the bread out of the oven, and let it cool for about 10 minutes before removing from the pan.
instructions\/27\/text: Serve warm, or at room temperature, by pulling the bread apart piece by piece.

instructions\/10\/text: Knead well for 10 minutes.
instructions\/11\/text: Sprinkle flour on the countertop sparingly as you knead.

instructions\/13\/text: To use the dough the same day, form the kneaded dough into a ball (or cut and form into four small balls for individual pizzas).
instructions\/14\/text: Spray a bowl with non stick spray, place the dough inside and turn it to coat with oil.
instructions\/15\/text: Cover the bowl loosely and let it rise in a warm place for one hour.
instructions\/16\/text: An hour later, after it has risen, punch it down to release some gasses and stretch it into a 16 round base.
instructions\/17\/text: Bake in a preheated (completely preheated, no short cuts here) oven at 230C for 10-12 minutes or until the edges are brown and crispy.
instructions\/18\/text: Making sure the oven is well heated before hand will ensure that the bottom cooks and gets nice and crispy.

instructions\/10\/text: Remove centers from the refrigerator to warm to room temperature before the next steps.
instructions\/11\/text: Melt 1 1/2 pounds of chopped chocolate and temper as follows.
instructions\/12\/text: If the chocolate is dull, grainy, or blemished, heat to at least 115 degrees.
instructions\/13\/text: When the chocolate is nearly melted, stir to complete the melt.
instructions\/14\/text: Let the chocolate cool to 100 degrees.
instructions\/15\/text: Look at the chunk of solid chocolate- it should be smooth, dark, and glossy, without dullness or streaking.
instructions\/16\/text: Submerge the 6 ounces of solid chocolate in the melted chocolate and stir until the chocolate cools to 90 degrees.
instructions\/17\/text: What this process does is isomerize the chocolate as it cools, so that the cooled shells will stay glossy and smooth, even in the refrigerator.
instructions\/18\/text: If the solid chunk is dull, streaky, or grained, it will have the opposite effect.
instructions\/19\/text: The taste will be the same, but tempering the chocolate makes the truffles much more attractive.
instructions\/20\/text: When the chocolate has cooled to 90 degrees, remove the chunk and save it for the next time you temper chocolate.
instructions\/21\/text: Smear a thin sample of the melted chocolate on wax paper and refrigerate for 2 minutes.
instructions\/22\/text: The smear should cool glossy and smooth, and should break with a snap.
instructions\/23\/text: Dip each truffle in chocolate; two forks seem to work the best for this (although I'd be interested in hearing anyone else's idea).
instructions\/24\/text: Top the truffles with cocoa or nuts if desired; if you plan to do this, do each truffle as you dip them, because they solidify fairly quickly.

title: Fruit Jewels (Pate De Fruit)
instructions\/1\/text: Mix together, then add the raspberries.
instructions\/2\/text: The raspberries will dominate the flavor.
instructions\/3\/text: If you want apricot-flavored Pate de Fruit, omit the raspberries.
instructions\/4\/text: Using a hand-held immersion blender or whisk, combine all of the ingredients until smooth and homogenous.
instructions\/5\/text: As the mixture cooks, the natural pectin in the fruit will cause the mixture to thicken.
instructions\/6\/text: Continue to cook until it is thick, mixing constantly.
instructions\/7\/text: To test for the correct consistency, dip a whisk in the mixture and hold horizontally in front of you.
instructions\/8\/text: Watch as the mixture drips off the whisk and back into the pan.
instructions\/9\/text: If the mixture stays on the whisk and beads up into small balls, like pearls, it is ready.
instructions\/10\/text: If it drips back into the pan in thin strands, it needs to be cooked a little longer.
instructions\/11\/text: When the mixture is a bit thicker than jam, pour it into a spouted container.
instructions\/12\/text: Fill either a half-dome or triangle shaped flexipan, depending on the desired design of the jewels and let rest for 4 hours at room temperature.
instructions\/13\/text: When the mixture has set, remove and roll each jewel in sugar.
instructions\/14\/text: If you do not have a flexipan, you can pour the Pate de Fruit into a 10-inch bottomless tart mold or cake ring placed on a parchment paper-covered baking sheet.
instructions\/15\/text: Let the Pate de Fruit cool and set, about 3 hours at room temperature.
instructions\/16\/text: When the mixture has set, remove and roll each jewel in sugar.
instructions\/17\/text: To unmold, run a sharp paring knife between the fruit and the mold and lift off the mold.
instructions\/18\/text: (At this point the Pate de Fruit can be stored, well wrapped in plastic and in an airtight container, for up to 2 months.)
instructions\/19\/text: Sprinkle the top of the Pate de Fruit with a thin layer of sugar and flip it onto another sheet of parchment paper.
instructions\/20\/text: Remove the parchment that is now on top.
instructions\/21\/text: Sprinkle this side with more sugar.
instructions\/22\/text: Using a wet chef's knife or cutter, cut the Pate de Fruit into any shapes.
instructions\/23\/text: Roll each piece completely in sugar and serve.
instructions\/24\/text: Do not store in the refrigerator, as the humidity will make the sugar melt.

instructions\/1\/text: Form into a ball and chill dough overnight in a sealed container.
instructions\/2\/text: (This is so the dough isnt so goopy and sticky & makes it easier to handle and roll out later).
instructions\/3\/text: Divide into four parts.
instructions\/4\/text: Take one part at a time and roll dough into a circle on a lightly floured surface (about 10-12 inches in diameter).
instructions\/5\/text: Cut into 12 wedges and roll up each wedge (start with large end) to form croissant shape.
instructions\/6\/text: Bake at 350F for approximately 20 minutes or until you notice nice golden brown spots forming (this is the cottage cheese).
instructions\/7\/text: Alternatively, you can freeze them and bake them at another time.
instructions\/8\/text: Personally, I find that I actually like them better when theyve been frozen.
instructions\/9\/text: For some reason, when you make them fresh, they turn out a little differently.
instructions\/10\/text: You also dont really need to thaw them out before baking for more than a few minutes.
instructions\/11\/text: Frost with icing.
instructions\/12\/text: Now, the icing is actually the part that makes these so good!
instructions\/13\/text: The rolls themselves are not sweet at all and really only transform into a dessert once the icing is added.
instructions\/14\/text: The icing happens to also be one of those things that I dont have a recipe for and sort of just wing it.
instructions\/15\/text: Its maybe roughly a cup of icing sugar, maybe 4 tablespoons of milk, and several dashes of cinnamon.
instructions\/16\/text: You can experiment with the amounts until you get something youre happy with.
instructions\/17\/text: These are best served fresh and warm out of the oven and I like them with a nice cold glass of milk!

title: Butter, Cultured
instructions\/1\/text: The cream will seperate some, and will sour.
instructions\/2\/text: This is a good thing!
instructions\/3\/text: Stir the cream to reincorporate the ingredients.
instructions\/4\/text: Begin to slowly whip the cream, by hand or using a stand-mixer.
instructions\/5\/text: When soft peaks begin to form whip faster.
instructions\/6\/text: The butter fat will begin to seperate from the butter milk -- continue to whip until you have pea sized chunks of the butter fat clinging to the side of the bowl.
instructions\/7\/text: This step may take some time, but be patient, it will happen!
instructions\/8\/text: Line a collander or strainer with cheesecloth and place your butter fat / butter milk into the cheesecloth (make sure to catch the butter milk!
instructions\/9\/text: you can use it for pancakes later!
instructions\/11\/text: Pull the ends of the cheese cloth together and press down to get rid of more of the butter milk.
instructions\/12\/text: You should now have a large hunk of very soft butter -- it's still got some butter milk incorporated into it, so --
instructions\/13\/text: You now want to rinse the butter under cold running water to remove more of the butter milk -- I do it a small handfull at a time, and I do it over a strainer or collander so I don't lose any small pieces.
instructions\/14\/text: It takes some practice, but you'll get the hang of it quickly.
instructions\/15\/text: After you've rinsed all the butter, place it in a mixing bowl and begin to press it up against the side of the bowl using a flat spoon or rubber spatula.
instructions\/16\/text: You'll release more butter milk and water this way, so make sure to drain that off as you go.
instructions\/17\/text: This is also the step where you will add any 'special' ingredients i.e.
instructions\/18\/text: salt, lavender, honey, whatever -- I prefer to make it un-salted, but recipezaar won't let me post a recipe with only one ingredient, so I'm listing salt --
instructions\/19\/text: when you're done with this step place the butter in some kind of mold (I use a cake pan lined with cheesecloth) and place it in the fridge.
instructions\/20\/text: after a few hours the butter will have set and if you want to cut it into smaller pieces you can do so --
instructions\/21\/text: This is an incredibly simplified version of the recipe that I use to make the butter that we sell at the shop I work at -- I make approximately double this recipe every week.
instructions\/22\/text: It's easy and, actually, kind of fun.
instructions\/23\/text: The end product will be much smoother and fresher than any butter you would buy at the store (unless, of course, you're shopping where I work :) .)
instructions\/24\/text: Starting with a better product will, of course, yield a better result.
instructions\/25\/text: I suggest using raw, organic, unpasteurized cream, if you can get it.
instructions\/26\/text: You will be pleasantly surprised with the result, and you will be doing your body, and the local economy, a favor.
instructions\/27\/text: A note about culturing -- you can omit this step if you like, but I reccomend trying it at least once.
instructions\/28\/text: I think if you do, you'll never go back.
instructions\/29\/text: It gives butter a characteristic flavor and a little more 'zing.'
instructions\/30\/text: I often have customers questioning this step saying things like "So you just let the milk go BAD?
instructions\/32\/text: I usually try to calm them by pointing out that this has been done for centuries with much success.
instructions\/33\/text: A note about temperature -- you will find it very difficult to do this recipe in a hot kitchen.
instructions\/34\/text: The butter will melt constantly and you'll lose more in the rinsing process.
instructions\/35\/text: At the same time, a cold kitchen will make it difficult as well.
instructions\/36\/text: I find that 70 to 75 degrees is the ideal temperature.
